NCBI_provided_description: Description of the equipment or method used to distribute water to livestock. This field accepts terms listed under water delivery equipment (http://opendata.inra.fr/EOL/EOL_0001653). Multiple terms can be separated by pipes

Name: food animal antimicrobial duration
NCBI_provided_description: The duration of time (days) that the antimicrobial was administered to the food animal

Name: food animal antimicrobial frequency
NCBI_provided_description: The frequency per day that the antimicrobial was adminstered to the food animal

Name: food animal antimicrobial route of administration
NCBI_provided_description: The route by which the antimicrobial is adminstered into the body of the food animal

Name: food animal antimicrobial intended use
NCBI_provided_description: The prescribed intended use of or the condition treated by the antimicrobial given to the food animal by any route of administration

Name: food animal body condition
NCBI_provided_description: Body condition scoring is a production management tool used to evaluate overall health and nutritional needs of a food animal, e.g., normal, over conditioned, under conditioned

Name: food animal source diet
NCBI_provided_description: If the isolate is from a food animal, the type of diet eaten by the food animal. Please list the main food staple and the setting, if appropriate. For a list of acceptable animal feed terms or categories, please see http://www.feedipedia.org. Multiple terms may apply and can be separated by pipes. Food product for animal covers foods intended for consumption by domesticated animals. Consult http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03309997. If the proper descriptor is not listed please use text to describe the food type. Multiple terms can be separated by one or more pipes. If the proper descriptor is not listed please use text to describe the food product type

Name: animal environment
NCBI_provided_description: The environment from which the animal sample was taken, e.g., veterinary clinic

Name: animal feeding equipment
NCBI_provided_description: Description of the feeding equipment used for livestock. This field accepts terms listed under feed delivery (http://opendata.inra.fr/EOL/EOL_0001757). Multiple terms can be separated by one or more pipes

Name: animal intrusion near sample source
NCBI_provided_description: Identification of animals intruding on the sample or sample site including invertebrates (such as pests or pollinators) and vertebrates (such as wildlife or domesticated animals). This field encourages terms under organism (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCIT_C14250). This field also encourages identification numbers from NCBI under https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/taxonomy. Multiple terms can be separated by pipes, e.g., large flies

Name: food animal source sex category
NCBI_provided_description: The sex and reproductive status of the food animal, e.g., castrated female, castrated male, intact female, intact male

Name: mean annual precipitation

NCBI_provided_description: mean annual and seasonal temperature (oC)

NCBI_provided_description: Mean annual temperature

NCBI_provided_description: An architectural structure is a human-made, free-standing, immobile outdoor construction, e.g., building, shed, home

NCBI_provided_description: Saturate, Aromatic, Resin and Asphaltene (SARA) is an analysis method that divides crude oil components according to their polarizability and polarity. There are three main methods to obtain SARA results. Name: asphaltenes wt%
NCBI_provided_description: Saturate, Aromatic, Resin and Asphaltene (SARA) is an analysis method that divides crude oil components according to their polarizability and polarity. There are three main methods to obtain SARA results. NCBI_provided_description: The cooling system identifier

NCBI_provided_description: Any result of a bacterial culture experiment reported as a binary assessment, e.g., absent, active, inactive, negative, no, present, positive, yes

Name: description
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: development stage
NCBI_provided_description: Developmental stage at the time of sampling.

Name: dew point
NCBI_provided_description: temperature to which a given parcel of humid air must be cooled, at constant barometric pressure, for water vapor to condense into water.

Name: diet
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: major diet change in last six months
NCBI_provided_description: specification of major diet changes in the last six months, if yes the change should be specified

Name: dietary claim or use
NCBI_provided_description: These descriptors are used either for foods intended for special dietary use as defined in 21 CFR 105 or for foods that have special characteristics indicated in the name or labeling. This field accepts terms listed under dietary claim or use (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03510023). Multiple terms can be separated by one or more pipes, but please consider limiting this list to the most prominent dietary claim or use

Name: diether lipids
NCBI_provided_description: concentration of diether lipids; can include multiple types of diether lipids

Name: not_included
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: disease
NCBI_provided_description: list of diseases diagnosed; can include multiple diagnoses. the value of the field depends on host; for humans the terms should be chosen from DO (Disease Ontology), free text for non-human. For DO terms, please see http://gemina.svn.sourceforge.net/viewvc/gemina/trunk/Gemina/ontologies/gemina_symptom.obo?view=log

Name: disease stage
NCBI_provided_description: stage of disease at the time of sampling.

Name: dissolved carbon dioxide
NCBI_provided_description: concentration of dissolved carbon dioxide

Name: dissolved hydrogen
NCBI_provided_description: concentration of dissolved hydrogen

Name: dissolved inorganic carbon
NCBI_provided_description: dissolved inorganic carbon concentration

Name: dissolved inorganic nitrogen
NCBI_provided_description: concentration of dissolved inorganic nitrogen

Name: dissolved inorganic phosphorus
NCBI_provided_description: concentration of dissolved inorganic phosphorus

Name: dissolved iron
NCBI_provided_description: Concentration of dissolved iron in the sample

Name: dissolved organic carbon
NCBI_provided_description: concentration of dissolved organic carbon

Name: dissolved organic nitrogen
NCBI_provided_description: dissolved organic nitrogen concentration measured as; total dissolved nitrogen - NH4 - NO3 - NO2

Name: dissolved oxygen
NCBI_provided_description: concentration of dissolved oxygen

Name: dissolved oxygen in fluids
NCBI_provided_description: Concentration of dissolved oxygen in the oil field produced fluids as it contributes to oxgen-corrosion and microbial activity, e.g. Mic

Name: dominant hand
NCBI_provided_description: dominant hand of the subject

Name: door type, composite
NCBI_provided_description: The composite type of the door, e.g., metal covered, revolving, sliding, telescopic

Name: door condition
NCBI_provided_description: The physical condition of the door, e.g., damaged, needs repair, new, rupture, visible wear

Name: door direction of opening
NCBI_provided_description: The direction the door opens, e.g., inward, outward, sideways

Name: door location
NCBI_provided_description: The relative location of the door in the room, e.g., north, south, east, west

Name: door material
NCBI_provided_description: The material the door is composed of, e.g., aluminum, cellular PVC, engineered plastic, fiberboard, fiberglass, metal, thermoplastic alloy, vinyl, wood, wood/plastic composite

Name: door movement
NCBI_provided_description: The type of movement of the door, e.g., collapsible, folding, revolving, rolling shutter, sliding, swinging

Name: door area or size
NCBI_provided_description: The size of the door

Name: door type
NCBI_provided_description: The type of door material, e.g., composite, metal, wooden

Name: door type, metal
NCBI_provided_description: The type of metal door, e.g., collapsible, corrugated steel, hollow, rolling shutters, steel plate

Name: door type, wood
NCBI_provided_description: The type of wood door, e.g., bettened and ledged, battened, ledged and braced, battened, ledged and framed, battened, ledged, braced and frame, framed and paneled, glashed or sash, flush, louvered, wire gauged

Name: door signs of water/mold
NCBI_provided_description: Signs of the presence of mold or mildew on a door, e.g., presence of mold visible, no presence of mold visible

Name: dose
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: douche
NCBI_provided_description: date of most recent douche

Name: downward PAR
NCBI_provided_description: visible waveband radiance and irradiance measurements in the water column

Name: drainage classification
NCBI_provided_description: drainage classification from a standard system such as the USDA system

Name: drawings
NCBI_provided_description: The buildings architectural drawings, e.g., operation, as built, construction, bid, design, building navigation map, diagram, sketch

Name: drug usage
NCBI_provided_description: any drug used by subject and the frequency of usage; can include multiple drugs used

Name: dry mass
NCBI_provided_description: measurement of dry mass

Name: ecotype
NCBI_provided_description: a population within a given species displaying genetically based, phenotypic traits that reflect adaptation to a local habitat, e.g., Columbia

Name: EDTA inhibitor tested
NCBI_provided_description: Was carbapenemase activity tested in the presence of EDTA? If carbapenemase activity was tested in the presence of EDTA, the response should be "yes", otherwise "no”.

Name: efficiency percent
NCBI_provided_description: percentage of volatile solids removed from the anaerobic digestor

Name: elevation
NCBI_provided_description: The elevation of the sampling site as measured by the vertical distance from mean sea level.

Name: elevator count
NCBI_provided_description: The number of elevators within the built structure

Name: emulsions
NCBI_provided_description: amount or concentration of substances such as paints, adhesives, mayonnaise, hair colorants, emulsified oils, etc.; can include multiple emulsion types

Name: encoded traits
NCBI_provided_description: Traits like antibiotic resistance/xenobiotic degration phenotypes/converting phage genes

Name: enrichment protocol
NCBI_provided_description: The microbiological workflow or protocol followed to test for the presence or enumeration of the target microbial analyte(s). Please provide a PubMed or DOI reference for published protocols

Name: not_included
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: broad-scale environmental context
NCBI_provided_description: Add terms that identify the major environment type(s) where your sample was collected. Recommend subclasses of biome [ENVO:00000428]. Multiple terms can be separated by one or more pipes e.g.:  mangrove biome [ENVO:01000181]|estuarine biome [ENVO:01000020]

Name: not_included
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: local-scale environmental context
NCBI_provided_description: Add terms that identify environmental entities having causal influences upon the entity at time of sampling, multiple terms can be separated by pipes, e.g.:  shoreline [ENVO:00000486]|intertidal zone [ENVO:00000316]

Name: not_included
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: environmental medium
NCBI_provided_description: Add terms that identify the material displaced by the entity at time of sampling. Recommend subclasses of environmental material [ENVO:00010483]. Multiple terms can be separated by pipes e.g.: estuarine water [ENVO:01000301]|estuarine mud [ENVO:00002160]

Name: food production environmental monitoring zone
NCBI_provided_description: An environmental monitoring zone is a formal designation as part of an environmental monitoring program, in which areas of a food production facility are categorized, commonly as zones 1-4, based on likelihood or risk of foodborne pathogen contamination. This field accepts entries of zones 1-4, e.g., Zone 1

Name: environmental package
NCBI_provided_description: MIGS/MIMS/MIENS extension for reporting of measurements and observations obtained from one or more of the environments where the sample was obtained. All environmental packages listed here are further defined in separate subtables. By giving the name of the environmental package, a selection of fields can be made from the subtables and can be reported

Name: escalator count
NCBI_provided_description: The number of escalators within the built structure

Name: estimated size
NCBI_provided_description: Estimated size of genome

Name: ethnicity
NCBI_provided_description: ethnicity of the subject

Name: ethylbenzene
NCBI_provided_description: Concentration of ethylbenzene in the sample

Name: exposed ductwork
NCBI_provided_description: The amount of exposed ductwork in the room

Name: exposed pipes
NCBI_provided_description: The number of exposed pipes in the room

Name: experimental factor
NCBI_provided_description: Variable aspect of experimental design

Name: exposure event
NCBI_provided_description: Event leading to exposure, e.g., mass gathering

Name: exterior door count
NCBI_provided_description: The number of exterior doors in the built structure

Name: orientations of exterior wall
NCBI_provided_description: The orientation of the exterior wall, e.g., north, south, east, west, northeast, southeast, southwest, northwest

Name: orientations of exterior window
NCBI_provided_description: The compass direction the exterior window of the room is facing, e.g., north, south, east, west, northeast, southeast, southwest, northwest

Name: extreme weather event
NCBI_provided_description: Unusual weather events that may have affected microbial populations. Multiple terms can be separated by pipes, listed in reverse chronological order, e.g., hail

Name: extrachromosomal elements
NCBI_provided_description: Plasmids that have significance phenotypic consequence

Name: extreme event
NCBI_provided_description: unusual physical events that may have affected microbial populations

Name: extreme salinity
NCBI_provided_description: measured salinity

Name: facility type
NCBI_provided_description: Establishment details about the type of facility where the sample was taken. This is independent of the specific product(s) within the facility, e.g., manufacturing-processing

Name: family id
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: family role
NCBI_provided_description: relationships to other samples in the same study; can include multiple relationships

Name: FAO classification
NCBI_provided_description: soil classification from the FAO World Reference Database for Soil Resources

Name: farm equipment used
NCBI_provided_description: List of relevant equipment used for planting, fertilization, harvesting, irrigation, land levelling, residue management, weeding or transplanting during the growing season. This field encourages terms listed under agricultural implement (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/AGRO_00000416). Multiple terms can be separated by pipes, e.g., combine harvester [AGRO:00000473]

Name: farm equipment sanitization
NCBI_provided_description: Method used to sanitize growing and harvesting equipment including type and concentration of sanitizing solution and frequency of sanitization

Name: farm equipment sanitization frequency
NCBI_provided_description: The number of times farm equipment is cleaned. Frequency of cleaning might be on a daily basis, weekly, monthly, quarterly or annually

Name: equipment shared with other farms
NCBI_provided_description: List of planting, growing or harvesting equipment shared with other farms

Name: farm watering water source
NCBI_provided_description: Source of water used on the farm for irrigation of crops or watering of livestock, e.g., water well

Name: fermentation chemical additives
NCBI_provided_description: Any chemicals that are added to the fermentation process to achieve the desired final product

Name: fermentation chemical additives percentage
NCBI_provided_description: The amount of chemical added to the fermentation process

Name: fermentation headspace oxygen
NCBI_provided_description: The amount of headspace oxygen in a fermentation vessel

Name: fermentation medium
NCBI_provided_description: The growth medium used for the fermented food fermentation process, which supplies the required nutrients. Usually this includes a carbon and nitrogen source, water, micronutrients and chemical additives

Name: fermentation pH
NCBI_provided_description: The pH of the fermented food fermentation process

Name: fermentation relative humidity
NCBI_provided_description: The relative humidity of the fermented food fermentation process

Name: fermentation temperature
NCBI_provided_description: The temperature of the fermented food fermentation process

Name: fermentation time
NCBI_provided_description: The time duration of the fermented food fermentation process

Name: fermentation vessel
NCBI_provided_description: The type of vessel used for containment of the fermentation

Name: fertilizer administration
NCBI_provided_description: Type of fertilizer or amendment added to the soil or water for the purpose of improving substrate health and quality for plant growth. This field encourages terms listed under agronomic fertilizer (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/AGRO_00002062). Multiple terms may apply and can be separated by pipes, listing in reverse chronological order, e.g., fish emulsion [AGRO:00000082]

Name: fertilizer administration date
NCBI_provided_description: Date of administration of soil amendment or fertilizer. Multiple terms may apply and can be separated by pipes, listing in reverse chronological order

Name: fertilizer regimen
NCBI_provided_description: information about treatment involving the use of fertilizers; should include the name fertilizer, amount administered, treatment duration, interval and total experimental duration; can include multiple fertilizer regimens

Name: field name
NCBI_provided_description: Name of the hydrocarbon field, e.g., Albacora

Name: filter type
NCBI_provided_description: device which removes solid particulates or airborne molecular contaminants
Format: ['', 'particulate air filter', 'chemical air filter', 'low-MERV pleated media', 'HEPA', 'electrostatic', 'gas-phase or ultraviolet air treatments', 'missing', 'not applicable', 'not collected', 'not provided', 'restricted access']

Name: fire
NCBI_provided_description: historical and/or physical evidence of fire

Name: fireplace type
NCBI_provided_description: A firebox with chimney, e.g., gas burning, wood burning

Name: flooding
NCBI_provided_description: historical and/or physical evidence of flooding

Name: floor age
NCBI_provided_description: The time period since installment of the carpet or flooring

Name: floor area
NCBI_provided_description: The area of the floor space within the room

Name: floor condition
NCBI_provided_description: The physical condition of the floor at the time of sampling, e.g., new, visible wear, needs repair, damaged, rupture

Name: floor count
NCBI_provided_description: The number of floors in the building, including basements and mechanical penthouse

Name: floor finish material
NCBI_provided_description: The floor covering type; the finished surface that is walked on, e.g., tile, wood strip or parquet, carpet, rug, laminate wood, lineoleum, vinyl composition tile, sheet vinyl, stone, bamboo, cork, terrazo, concrete, none;specify unfinished, sealed, clear finish, paint

Name: floor structure
NCBI_provided_description: Refers to the structural elements and subfloor upon which the finish flooring is installed, e.g., balcony, floating floor, glass floor, raised floor, sprung floor, wood-framed, concrete

Name: floor thermal mass
NCBI_provided_description: The ability of the floor to provide inertia against temperature fluctuations

Name: floor signs of water/mold
NCBI_provided_description: Signs of the presence of mold or mildew in a room, e.g., mold odor, wet floor, water stains, wall discoloration, floor discoloration, ceiling discoloration, peeling paint or wallpaper, bulging walls, condensation

Name: fluorescence
NCBI_provided_description: raw or converted fluorescence of water

Name: fetal health status
NCBI_provided_description: specification of foetal health status, should also include abortion

Name: food additive
NCBI_provided_description: A substance or substances added to food to maintain or improve safety and freshness, to improve or maintain nutritional value, or improve taste, texture and appearance. This field encourages terms listed under food additive (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03412972). Multiple terms can be separated by one or more pipes, but please consider limiting this list to the top 5 ingredients listed in order as on the food label. See also, https://www.fda.gov/food/food-ingredients-packaging/overview-food-ingredients-additives-colors, e.g., xanthan gum [FOODON:03413321]

Name: food allergen labeling
NCBI_provided_description: A label indication that the product contains a recognized allergen. This field accepts terms listed under dietary claim or use (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03510213)

Name: food cleaning process
NCBI_provided_description: The process of cleaning food to separate other environmental materials from the food source. Multiple terms can be separated by pipes, e.g., rinsed with water|scrubbed with brush

Name: food contact surface
NCBI_provided_description: The specific container or coating materials in direct contact with the food. Multiple values can be assigned. This field encourages terms listed under food contact surface (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03500010), e.g., aluminum surface [FOODON:03500042]

Name: food container or wrapping
NCBI_provided_description: Type of container or wrapping defined by the main container material, the container form, and the material of the liner lids or ends. Also type of container or wrapping by form; prefer description by material first, then by form. This field encourages terms listed under food container or wrapping (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03490100), e.g., bottle or jar [FOODON:03490203]

Name: food cooking process
NCBI_provided_description: The transformation of raw food by the application of heat. This field encourages terms listed under food cooking (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03450002), e.g., food blanching [FOODON:03470175]

Name: food distribution point geographic location
NCBI_provided_description: A reference to a place on the Earth, by its name or by its geographical location that refers to a distribution point along the food chain. This field accepts terms listed under geographic location (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GAZ_00000448). Reference: Adam Diamond, James Barham. Moving Food Along the Value Chain: Innovations in Regional Food Distribution. U.S. Dept. of Agriculture, Agricultural Marketing Service. Washington, DC. March 2012. http://dx.doi.org/10.9752/MS045.03-2012

Name: food distribution point geographic location (city)
NCBI_provided_description: A reference to a place on the Earth, by its name or by its geographical location that refers to a distribution point along the food chain. This field accepts terms listed under geographic location (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GAZ_00000448). Reference: Adam Diamond, James Barham. Moving Food Along the Value Chain: Innovations in Regional Food Distribution. U.S. Dept. of Agriculture, Agricultural Marketing Service. Washington, DC. March 2012. http://dx.doi.org/10.9752/MS045.03-2012

Name: Food harvesting process
NCBI_provided_description: A harvesting process is a process which takes in some food material from an individual or community of plant or animal organisms in a given context and time, and outputs a precursor or consumable food product. This may include a part of an organism or the whole, and may involve killing the organism

Name: FDA food industry class name
NCBI_provided_description: The US FDA Class is the second of five elements that comprise a FDA product code. This element is directly related to an Industry and designates the food group, source, product, use, pharmacological action, category or animal species of the product. A Class code is more specific than an Industry; for example, the Fishery/Seafood products Industry may contain Classes such as Smoked, Breaded and such, e.g., Coffee, Decaffeinated

Name: FDA food industry code name
NCBI_provided_description: The US FDA Industry Code is the first of five elements that comprise an FDA product code. An Industry code determines the broadest area into which a product falls, e.g., 31 Coffee and Tea

Name: food ingredient
NCBI_provided_description: In this field, please list individual ingredients for multi-component food [FOODON:00002501] and simple foods that is not captured in food_type. Please use terms that are present in FoodOn. Multiple terms can be separated by one or more pipes, but please consider limiting this list to the top 5 ingredients listed in order as on the food label. See also, https://www.fda.gov/food/food-ingredients-packaging/overview-food-ingredients-additives-colors

Name: food product name legal status
NCBI_provided_description: A datum indicating that use of a food product name is regulated in some legal jurisdiction. This field accepts terms listed under food product name legal status (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03530087)

Name: food product origin geographic location
NCBI_provided_description: A reference to a place on the Earth, by its name or by its geographical location that describes the origin of the food commodity, either in terms of its cultivation or production. This field encourages terms listed under geographic location (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GAZ_00000448), e.g., Thailand

Name: food package capacity
NCBI_provided_description: The maximum number of product units within a package

Name: food packing integrity
NCBI_provided_description: A term label and term id to describe the state of the packing material and text to explain the exact condition. This field encourages terms listed under food packing medium integrity (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03530218), e.g., food packing medium compromised [FOODON:00002517]

Name: food packing medium
NCBI_provided_description: The medium in which the food is packed for preservation and handling or the medium surrounding homemade foods, e.g., peaches cooked in sugar syrup. The packing medium may provide a controlled environment for the food. It may also serve to improve palatability and consumer appeal. This includes edible packing media (e.g. fruit juice), gas other than air (e.g. carbon dioxide), vacuum packed, or packed with aerosol propellant. This field encourages terms under food packing medium (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03480020). Multiple terms may apply and can be separated by pipes, e.g., vacuum-packed [FOODON:03480027]

Name: food preservation process
NCBI_provided_description: The methods contributing to the prevention or retardation of microbial, enzymatic or oxidative spoilage and thus to the extension of shelf life. This field encourages terms listed under food preservation process (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03470107), e.g., food fermentation [FOODON:00001304]

Name: material of contact prior to food packaging
NCBI_provided_description: The material the food contacted (e.g., was processed in) prior to packaging. This field accepts terms listed under material of contact prior to food packaging (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03530077). If the proper descriptor is not listed please use text to describe the material of contact prior to food packaging

Name: food processing method
NCBI_provided_description: Methods for processing food, e.g., food (blanched) [FOODON:00002767]

Name: food production system
NCBI_provided_description: Descriptors of the food production system or of the agricultural environment and growing conditions related to the farm production system. This field encourages terms listed under food production (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03530206). Multiple terms may apply and can be separated by pipes, e.g., restaurant food preparation process [FOODON:03530110]

Name: food production characteristics
NCBI_provided_description: Descriptors of the food production system such as wild caught, free-range, organic, free-range, industrial, dairy, beef

Name: food product synonym
NCBI_provided_description: Other names by which the food product is known by (e.g., regional or non-English names), e.g., pinot gris

Name: food product by quality
NCBI_provided_description: Descriptors for describing food visually or via other senses, which is useful for tasks like food inspection where little prior knowledge of how the food came to be is available. Some terms like "food (frozen)" are both a quality descriptor and the output of a process. This field accepts terms listed under food product by quality (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_00002454)

Name: food product type
NCBI_provided_description: A food product type is a class of food products that is differentiated by its food composition (e.g., single- or multi-ingredient), processing and/or consumption characteristics. This does not include brand name products but it may include generic food dish categories. This field encourages terms under food product type (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON:03400361). For terms related to food product for an animal, consult food product for animal (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03309997). If the proper descriptor is not listed please use text to describe the food type. Multiple terms can be separated by one or more pipes, e.g., multi-component food product [FOODON:00002501]

Name: food quality date
NCBI_provided_description: The date recommended for the use of the product while at peak quality, this date is not a reflection of safety unless used on infant formula this date is not a reflection of safety and is typically labeled on a food product as ""best if used by,"" best by,"" ""use by,"" or ""freeze by"", e.g., 5/24/2020

Name: food source
NCBI_provided_description: Individual organism or category of organisms from which the food product or its major ingredient is derived, e.g., giant tiger prawn [FOODON:03412612]

Name: food source age
NCBI_provided_description: The age of the food source host organim. Depending on the type of host organism, age may be more appropriate to report in days, weeks, or years

Name: food traceability list category
NCBI_provided_description: The FDA is proposing to establish additional traceability recordkeeping requirements (beyond what is already required in existing regulations) for persons who manufacture, process, pack, or hold foods the Agency has designated for inclusion on the Food Traceability List. The Food Traceability List (FTL) identifies the foods for which the additional traceability records described in the proposed rule would be required. The term ""Food Traceability List"" (FTL) refers not only to the foods specifically listed (https://www.fda.gov/media/142303/download), but also to any foods that contain listed foods as ingredients, e.g., tropical tree fruits

Name: food shipping transportation method
NCBI_provided_description: A descriptor for the method of movement of food commodity along the food distribution system. This field accepts terms listed under travel mode (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GENEPIO_0001064). If the proper descrptor is not listed please use text to describe the mode of travel. Multiple terms can be separated by one or more pipes

Name: food shipping transportation vehicle
NCBI_provided_description: A descriptor for the mobile machine which is used to transport food commodities along the food distribution system. This field accepts terms listed under vehicle (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_01000604). If the proper descrptor is not listed please use text to describe the mode of travel. Multiple terms can be separated by one or more pipes

Name: food treatment process
NCBI_provided_description: Used to specifically characterize a food product based on the treatment or processes applied to the product or any indexed ingredient. The processes include adding, substituting or removing components or modifying the food or component, e.g., through fermentation. Multiple values can be assigned. This fields accepts terms listed under food treatment process (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03460111)

Name: food type processed in facility
NCBI_provided_description: Food type processed in facility, e.g., dairy

Name: forma
NCBI_provided_description: Taxonomy level below subspecies (or variety in botany). Use is similar to ecotype etc.

Name: forma specialis
NCBI_provided_description: Usually applied to fungus adapted to a specific host.

Name: frequency of cleaning
NCBI_provided_description: The number of times the sample location is cleaned, e.g., daily, weekly, monthly, quarterly, annually

Name: frequency of cooking
NCBI_provided_description: The number of times a meal is cooked per week

Name: fungicide regimen
NCBI_provided_description: information about treatment involving use of fungicides; should include the name of fungicide, amount administered, treatment duration, interval and total experimental duration; can include multiple fungicide regimens

Name: furniture
NCBI_provided_description: The types of furniture present in the sampled room, e.g., cabinet, chair, desks

Name: gap accession
NCBI_provided_description: technical dictionary

Name: gap change status
NCBI_provided_description: technical dictionary

Name: gap consent code
NCBI_provided_description: technical dictionary

Name: gap consent short name
NCBI_provided_description: technical dictionary

Name: gap sample id
NCBI_provided_description: technical dictionary

Name: gap study version
NCBI_provided_description: technical dictionary

Name: gap subject id
NCBI_provided_description: technical dictionary

Name: gaseous environment
NCBI_provided_description: use of conditions with differing gaseous environments; should include the name of gaseous compound, amount administered, treatment duration, interval and total experimental duration; can include multiple gaseous environment regimens

Name: gaseous substances
NCBI_provided_description: amount or concentration of substances such as hydrogen sulfide, carbon dioxide, methane, etc.; can include multiple substances

Name: gastrointestinal tract disorder
NCBI_provided_description: history of gastrointestinal tract disorders; can include multiple disorders

Name: gender of restroom
NCBI_provided_description: The gender type of the restroom, e.g., all gender, female, gender neutral, male, male and female, unisex

Name: genetic modification
NCBI_provided_description: Genetic modifications of the genome of an organism, which may occur naturally by spontaneous mutation, or be introduced by some experimental means, e.g. specification of a transgene or the gene knocked-out or details of transient transfection

Name: genotype
NCBI_provided_description: observed genotype

Name: geo loc exposure
NCBI_provided_description: The country where the host was likely exposed to the causative agent of the illness. This location pertains to the country the host was believed to be exposed, and may not be the same as the host's country of residence, e.g., Canada

Name: geographic location
NCBI_provided_description: Geographical origin of the sample; use the appropriate name from this list http://www.insdc.org/documents/country-qualifier-vocabulary. Use a colon to separate the country or ocean from more detailed information about the location, eg "Canada: Vancouver" or "Germany: halfway down Zugspitze, Alps"

Name: gestation state
NCBI_provided_description: specification of the gestation state

Name: GISAID accession
NCBI_provided_description: The GISAID accession assigned to the sequence. GISAID Accession Numbers are used as unique and permanent identifiers for each virus beginning with the letters EPI and followed by numbers, to identify viruses and/or segments; https://www.gisaid.org/; e.g., EPI_ISL_1091361

Name: GISAID virus name
NCBI_provided_description: The full virus name submitted to GISAID (https://www.gisaid.org/), e.g., hCoV-19/Belgium/rega-3187/2021

Name: glucosidase activity
NCBI_provided_description: measurement of glucosidase activity

Name: gravidity
NCBI_provided_description: whether or not subject is gravid, and if yes date due or date post-conception, specifying which is used

Name: gravity
NCBI_provided_description: information about treatment involving use of gravity factor to study various types of responses in presence, absence or modified levels of gravity; can include multiple treatments

Name: growth facility
NCBI_provided_description: Type of facility where the sampled plant was grown; controlled vocabulary: growth chamber, open top chamber, glasshouse, experimental garden, field. Alternatively use Crop Ontology (CO) terms, see http://www.cropontology.org/ontology/CO_715/Crop%20Research

Name: growth habit
NCBI_provided_description: Characteristic shape, appearance or growth form of a plant species, e.g., erect, semi-erect, spreading, prostrate

Name: growth hormone regimen
NCBI_provided_description: information about treatment involving use of growth hormones; should include the name of growth hormone, amount administered, treatment duration, interval and total experimental duration; can include multiple growth hormone regimens

Name: growth media

Multiple co-infecting species may be added in a comma-separated list. For listing symbiotic organisms associated with the host (A) use the term Observed host symbiont

Name: host of the symbiotic host local environmental context
NCBI_provided_description: For a symbiotic host organism the local anatomical environment within its host may have causal influences. Report the anatomical entity(s) which are in the direct environment of the symbiotic host organism being sampled and which you believe have significant causal influences on your sample or specimen. For example, if the symbiotic host organism being sampled is an intestinal worm, its local environmental context will be the term for intestine from UBERON (http://uberon.github.io/)

Name: host of the symbiotic host environemental medium
NCBI_provided_description: Report the environmental material(s) immediately surrounding the symbiotic host organism at the time of sampling. This usually will be a tissue or substance type from the host, but may be another material if the symbiont is external to the host. We recommend using classes from the UBERON ontology, but subclasses of 'environmental material' (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ENVO_00010483) may also be used. EnvO documentation about how to use the field: https://github.com/EnvironmentOntology/envo/wiki/Using-ENVO-with-MIxS. Terms from other OBO ontologies are permissible as long as they reference mass/volume nouns (e.g., air, water, blood) and not discrete, countable entities (e.g., intestines, heart)

If the specimen was destroyed in the process of analysis, electronic images (e-vouchers) are an adequate substitute for a physical host voucher specimen. If a URI is not available, a museum-provided globally unique identifier (GUID) can be used. URI example: http://portal.vertnet.org/o/fmnh/mammals?id=33e55cfe-330b-40d9-aaae-8d042cba7542; INSDC triplet example: UAM:Mamm:52179

Subspecies should not be recorded in this term, but in the NCBI taxonomy. Supply both the lineage name and the lineage rank separated by a colon, e.g., biovar:abc123

Name: Interagency Food Safety Analytics Collaboration (IFSAC) category
NCBI_provided_description: The IFSAC food categorization scheme has five distinct levels to which foods can be assigned, depending upon the type of food. First, foods are assigned to one of four food groups (aquatic animals, land animals, plants, and other). Food groups include increasingly specific food categories; dairy, eggs, meat and poultry, and game are in the land animal food group, and the category meat and poultry is further subdivided into more specific categories of meat (beef, pork, other meat) and poultry (chicken, turkey, other poultry). Finally, foods are differentiated by differences in food processing (such as pasteurized fluid dairy products, unpasteurized fluid dairy products, pasteurized solid and semi-solid dairy products, and unpasteurized solid and semi-solid dairy products. An IFSAC food category chart is available from https://www.cdc.gov/foodsafety/ifsac/projects/food-categorization-scheme.html PMID: 28926300, e.g., Plants:Produce:Vegetables:Herbs:Dried Herbs

NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: outbreak

Name: particulate organic carbon

Name: particulate organic nitrogen

Name: part of plant or animal
NCBI_provided_description: The anatomical part of the organism being involved in food production or consumption; e.g., a carrot is the root of the plant (root vegetable). This field accepts terms listed under part of plant or animal (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03420116)

Name: particle classification
NCBI_provided_description: particles are classified, based on their size, into six general categories:clay, silt, sand, gravel, cobbles, and boulders; should include amount of particle preceded by the name of the particle type; can include multiple values

Name: passage history

Name: passage method
NCBI_provided_description: Description of how the organism was passaged. Provide a short description, e.g., AVL buffer+30%EtOH lysate received from Respiratory Lab. P3 passage in Vero-1 via bioreactor large-scale batch passage. P3 batch derived from the SP-2/reference lab strain. If not passaged, put ""not applicable"".

NCBI_provided_description: The number of known passages, e.g., 3. If not passaged, put ""not applicable"".

Name: pathogenicity
NCBI_provided_description: To what is the entity pathogenic

Name: pathotype
NCBI_provided_description: Some bacterial specific pathotypes (example Eschericia coli - STEC, UPEC)

Name: pathovar
NCBI_provided_description: Taxonomy below subspecies; a variety (in bacteria, fungi or virus) usually based on its pathogenic properties. Sometimes used as equivalent to subspecies.

Name: permeability
NCBI_provided_description: Measure of the ability of a hydrocarbon resource to allow fluids to pass through it. Additional information: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Permeability_(earth_sciences)

Name: perturbation
NCBI_provided_description: type of perturbation, e.g. chemical administration, physical disturbance, etc., coupled with time that perturbation occurred; can include multiple perturbation types

NCBI_provided_description: concentration of petroleum hydrocarbon

Name: pH
NCBI_provided_description: pH measurement

Name: pH regimen

Name: phenotype
NCBI_provided_description: Phenotype of sampled organism. For Phenotypic quality Ontology (PATO) (v1.269) terms, please see http://bioportal.bioontology.org/visualize/44601

Name: phosphate
NCBI_provided_description: concentration of phosphate

Name: phospholipid fatty acid
NCBI_provided_description: concentration of phospholipid fatty acids; can include multiple values

Name: photon flux
NCBI_provided_description: measurement of photon flux

Name: photosynthetic activity
NCBI_provided_description: Measurement of photosythetic activity (i.e. leaf gas exchange / chlorophyll fluorescence emissions / reflectance / transpiration) Please also include the term method term detailing the method of activity measurement

Name: photosynthetic activity method
NCBI_provided_description: Reference or method used in measurement of photosythetic activity

Name: plant body site
NCBI_provided_description: name of body site that the sample was obtained from. For Plant Ontology (PO) (v 20) terms, see http://purl.bioontology.org/ontology/PO

Name: plant growth medium
NCBI_provided_description: Type of the media used for growing sampled plants, e.g., soil [ENVO:00001998]

Name: degree of plant part maturity
NCBI_provided_description: A description of the stage of development of a plant or plant part based on maturity or ripeness. This field accepts terms listed under degree of plant maturity (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/FOODON_03530050)

Name: plant product
NCBI_provided_description: substance produced by the plant, where the sample was obtained from

Name: plant reproductive part
NCBI_provided_description: Plant reproductive part used in the field during planting to start the crop, e.g., plant cutting, pregerminated seed, ratoon, seed, seedling, whole mature plant

Name: plant sex
NCBI_provided_description: Sex of the reproductive parts on the whole plant, e.g., androdioecious, androecious, androgynous, androgynomonoecious, andromonoecious, bisexual, dichogamous, diclinous, dioecious, gynodioecious, gynoecious, gynomonoecious, hermaphroditic, imperfect, monoclinous, monoecious, perfect, polygamodioecious, polygamomonoecious, polygamous, protandrous, protogynous, subandroecious, subdioecious, subgynoecious, synoecious, trimonoecious, trioecious, unisexual

Name: plant structure
NCBI_provided_description: Name of plant structure the sample was obtained from; for Plant Ontology (PO) (v releases/2017-12-14) terms, see http://purl.bioontology.org/ontology/PO, e.g., petiole epidermis (PO_0000051). If an individual flower is sampled, the sex of it can be recorded here

Name: plant water delivery method
NCBI_provided_description: Description of the equipment or method used to distribute water to crops. This field encourages terms listed under irrigation process (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/AGRO_00000006). Multiple terms can be separated by pipes, e.g., drip irrigation process [AGRO:00000056]

Name: ploidy
NCBI_provided_description: Ploidy level of genome (eg., haploid, diploid)

Name: pollutants
NCBI_provided_description: pollutant types and, amount or concentrations measured at the time of sampling; can report multiple pollutants by entering numeric values preceded by name of pollutant

Name: pooling of DNA extracts
NCBI_provided_description: were multiple DNA extractions mixed? how many?

Name: population
NCBI_provided_description: for human: ; for plants: filial generation, number of progeny, genetic structure

Name: Population Description
NCBI_provided_description: The full, unabbreviated population descriptor from the Coriell Institute

Name: porosity
NCBI_provided_description: porosity of deposited sediment is volume of voids divided by the total volume of sample

Name: positive control type
NCBI_provided_description: The substance, mixture, product, or apparatus used to verify that a process which is part of an investigation delivers a true positive

Name: potassium
NCBI_provided_description: concentration of potassium

Name: pour point
NCBI_provided_description: Temperature at which a liquid becomes semi solid and loses its flow characteristics. In crude oil a high pour point is generally associated with a high paraffin content, typically found in crude deriving from a larger proportion of plant material (source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/pour_point)

Name: pretreatment
NCBI_provided_description: the process of pre-treatment removes materials that can be easily collected from the raw wastewater

Name: pregnancy
NCBI_provided_description: date due of pregnancy

Name: presence of pets, animals, or insects
NCBI_provided_description: The type and number of animals or insects present in the sampling space, e.g., cat 10, dog 2, rodent 100, snake 1

Name: pressure
NCBI_provided_description: pressure to which the sample is subject, in atmospheres

Name: previous land use
NCBI_provided_description: previous land use and dates

Name: previous land use method
NCBI_provided_description: reference or method used in determining previous land use and dates

Name: primary production
NCBI_provided_description: measurement of primary production

Name: primary treatment
NCBI_provided_description: the process to produce both a generally homogeneous liquid capable of being treated biologically and a sludge that can be separately treated or processed

Name: prior SARS-CoV-2 antiviral treatment
NCBI_provided_description: Has the host received SARS-CoV-2 antiviral treatment?

Name: prior SARS-CoV-2 infection
NCBI_provided_description: Did the host have a prior SARS-CoV-2 infection?

Name: prior SARS-CoV-2 vaccination
NCBI_provided_description: Has the host received a SARS-CoV-2 vaccination?

Name: production labeling claims
NCBI_provided_description: Labeling claims containing descriptors such as wild caught, free-range, organic, free-range, industrial, hormone-free, antibiotic free, cage free

NCBI_provided_description: Oil and/or gas production rates per well, e.g., 524 m3/day

Name: production start date
NCBI_provided_description: Date of field's first production

Name: profile position
NCBI_provided_description: cross-sectional position in the hillslope where sample was collected.sample area position in relation to surrounding areas

Name: project name
NCBI_provided_description: A concise name that describes the overall project, for example "Analysis of sequences collected from Antarctic soil"

Name: propagation

Name: pulmonary disorder
NCBI_provided_description: history of pulmonary disorders; can include multiple disorders

Name: pulse

Name: purpose of sampling
NCBI_provided_description: the reason that the sample was collected, e.g., active surveillance in response to an outbreak, active surveillance not initiated by an outbreak, clinical trial, cluster investigation, environmental assessment, farm sample, field trial, for cause, industry internal investigation, market sample, passive surveillance, population based studies, research, research and development

Name: purpose of sequencing
NCBI_provided_description: The reason the sample was sequenced, e.g., baseline surveillance (random sampling)

Name: purpose of wastewater sampling
NCBI_provided_description: The reason the sample was collected
Format: ['', 'public health surveillance community-level', 'public health surveillance institution-level', 'public health surveillance building-level', 'research', 'other', 'missing', 'not applicable', 'not collected', 'not provided', 'restricted access']

Name: purpose of wastewater sequencing
NCBI_provided_description: The reason the sample was sequenced, e.g., identification of mutations within a specific region, presence of clinically known mutations, or diversity of mutations across entire genome

Name: race

Name: rainfall regimen
NCBI_provided_description: information about treatment involving an exposure to a given amount of rainfall; can include multiple regimens

Name: reactor type

Name: redox potential

Name: reference for biomaterial

Name: reference material
NCBI_provided_description: Indicates that a standards body or external group asserts this sample is reference material, eg, 'NIST reference material for genome sequencing validation'.

Name: relative air humidity
NCBI_provided_description: partial vapor and air pressure, density of the vapor and air, or by the actual mass of the vapor and air

Name: outside relative humidity
NCBI_provided_description: The recorded outside relative humidity value at the time of sampling

Name: relative location of sample
NCBI_provided_description: Location of sample to other parts of the farm, e.g. under crop plant, near irrigation ditch, from the dirt road, from air above crops, nearby river, e.g., furrow

Name: relative sampling location
NCBI_provided_description: The sampling location within the train car, e.g., edge of car, center of car, under a seat

Name: relationship to oxygen
NCBI_provided_description: Is this organism an aerobe, anaerobe? Please note that aerobic and anaerobic are valid descriptors for microbial environments, eg, aerobe, anaerobe, facultative, microaerophilic, microanaerobe, obligate aerobe, obligate anaerobe, missing, not applicable, not collected, not provided, restricted access
Format: ['', 'aerobe', 'anaerobe', 'facultative', 'microaerophilic', 'microanaerobe', 'obligate aerobe', 'obligate anaerobe', 'missing', 'not applicable', 'not collected', 'not provided', 'restricted access']

Name: repository

Name: reservoir name
NCBI_provided_description: Name of the reservoir, e.g., Carapebus

Name: resins wt%
NCBI_provided_description: Saturate, Aromatic, Resin and Asphaltene (SARA) is an analysis method that divides crude oil components according to their polarizability and polarity. There are three main methods to obtain SARA results. The most popular one is known as the Iatroscan TLC-FID and is referred to as IP-143 (source: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saturate,_aromatic,_resin_and_asphaltene)

Name: risk group
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

NCBI_provided_description: List of rooms connected to the sampling room by a doorway, e.g., attic, bathroom, closet, conference room, elevator, examining room, hallway, kitchen, mail room, office, stairwell

Name: room count
NCBI_provided_description: The total count of rooms in the built structure including all room types

Name: room dimensions
NCBI_provided_description: The length, width and height of sampling room

NCBI_provided_description: Distance between doors (meters) in the hallway between the sampling room and adjacent rooms

NCBI_provided_description: List of room(s) (room number, room name) sharing a door with the sampling room

Name: room location in building
NCBI_provided_description: The position of the room within the building, e.g., corner room, interior room, exterior wall

Name: room type
NCBI_provided_description: The main purpose or activity of the sampling room. A room is any distinguishable space within a structure, e.g., attic, bathroom, closet, conference room, elevator, examining room, hallway, kitchen, mail room, private office, open office, stairwell,restroom, lobby, vestibule, mechanical or electrical room, data center, laboratory_wet, laboratory_dry, gymnasium, natatorium, auditorium, lockers, cafe, warehouse

Name: room volume
NCBI_provided_description: Volume of sampling room

Name: rooms that share a wall with sampling room
NCBI_provided_description: List of room(s) (room number, room name) sharing a wall with the sampling room

Name: room window count
NCBI_provided_description: Number of windows in the room

NCBI_provided_description: Relevant rooting conditions such as field plot size, sowing density, container dimensions, number of plants per container

NCBI_provided_description: Source of organic carbon in the culture rooting medium, e.g., sucrose

NCBI_provided_description: Measurement of the culture rooting medium macronutrients (N,P, K, Ca, Mg, S), e.g., KH2PO4 (170mg/L)

Name: rooting medium micronutrients
NCBI_provided_description: Measurement of the culture rooting medium micronutrients (Fe, Mn, Zn, B, Cu, Mo), e.g., H3BO3 (6.2mg/L)

Name: rooting medium pH
NCBI_provided_description: pH measurement of the culture rooting medium, e.g., 5.5

Name: rooting medium regulators
NCBI_provided_description: Growth regulators in the culture rooting medium such as cytokinins, auxins, gybberellins, abscisic acid, e.g., 0.5 mg/L NAA

Name: rooting medium solidifier
NCBI_provided_description: Specification of the solidifying agent in the culture rooting medium, e.g., agar

NCBI_provided_description: Organic supplements of the culture rooting medium, such as vitamins, amino acids, organic acids, antibiotics activated charcoal, e.g., nicotinic acid (0.5 mg/L)

Name: route of transmission
NCBI_provided_description: Description of path taken by the symbiotic host organism being sampled in order to establish a symbiotic relationship with the host (with which it was observed at the time of sampling) via a mode of transmission (specified in mode_transmission), e.g., environmental:faecal-oral, transplacental, vector-borne:vector penetration

Name: salinity

Name: same as
NCBI_provided_description: indicates that the same physical sample has multiple BioSample records

Name: sample capture status
NCBI_provided_description: Reason for the sample, e.g., active surveillance in response to an outbreak, active surveillance not initiated by an outbreak, farm sample, market sample

NCBI_provided_description: Method or device employed for collecting sample

Name: sample collection method
NCBI_provided_description: The method employed for collecting the sample

Name: sample collection point
NCBI_provided_description: Sampling point on the asset where sample was collected, e.g., well, test well, drilling rig, wellhead, separator, storage tank

Name: sample disease stage
NCBI_provided_description: Stage of the disease at the time of sample collection, e.g., dissemination, growth and reproduction, infection, inoculation, penetration

Name: sampling floor
NCBI_provided_description: The floor of the building, where the sampling room is located, e.g., 1st floor, 2nd floor, basement, lobby

Name: sample location condition
NCBI_provided_description: The condition of the sample location at the time of sampling, e.g., damaged, new, rupture, visible signs of mold-mildew, visible weariness repair

Name: corrosion rate at sample location
NCBI_provided_description: Metal corrosion rate is the speed of metal deterioration due to environmental conditions. As environmental conditions change corrosion rates change accordingly. Therefore, long term corrosion rates are generally more informative than short term rates and for that reason they are preferred during reporting. In the case of suspected MIC, corrosion rate measurements at the time of sampling might provide insights into the involvement of certain microbial community members in MIC as well as potential microbial interplays

Name: sample material processing
NCBI_provided_description: Processing applied to the sample during or after isolation

Name: sample material type (host or environmental context)
NCBI_provided_description: The type of material from which the sample was obtained. For the Hydrocarbon package, samples include types like core, rock trimmings, drill cuttings, piping section, coupon, pigging debris, solid deposit, produced fluid, produced water, injected water, swabs, etc. For the Food Package, samples are usually categorized as food, body products or tissues, or environmental material. This field accepts terms listed under environmental specimen (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GENEPIO_0001246)

Name: sample measured depth
NCBI_provided_description: In non deviated well, measured depth is equal to the true vertical depth, TVD (TVD=TVDSS plus the reference or datum it refers to). In deviated wells, the MD is the length of trajectory of the borehole measured from the same reference or datum. Common datums used are ground level (GL), drilling rig floor (DF), rotary table (RT), kelly bushing (KB) and mean sea level (MSL). If "other" is specified, please propose entry in "additional info" field

Name: sample pooling
NCBI_provided_description: Physical combination of several instances of like material, e.g., RNA extracted from samples or dishes of cell cultures into one big aliquot of cells. Please provide a short description of the samples that were pooled

Name: preservative added to sample
NCBI_provided_description: Preservative added to the sample, e.g. Rnalater, alcohol, formaldehyde. Where appropriate include volume added, e.g. Rnalater; 2 ml

Name: biological sample replicate
NCBI_provided_description: Measurements of biologically distinct samples that show biological variation

Name: technical sample replicate
NCBI_provided_description: Repeated measurements of the same sample that show independent measures of the noise associated with the equipment and the protocols

Name: sampling room ID or name
NCBI_provided_description: Sampling room number. This ID should be consistent with the designations on the building floor plans

Name: sample salinity
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: sample size
NCBI_provided_description: Amount or size of sample (volume, mass or area) that was collected

Name: sample size sorting method
NCBI_provided_description: method by which samples are sorted

Name: sample source material category
NCBI_provided_description: This is the scientific role or category that the subject organism or material has with respect to an investigation. Name: sample storage device
NCBI_provided_description: The container used to store the sample. This field accepts terms listed under container (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCIT_C43186). If the proper descriptor is not listed please use text to describe the storage device

Name: sample storage media
NCBI_provided_description: The liquid that is added to the sample collection device prior to sampling. If the sample is pre-hydrated, indicate the liquid media the sample is pre-hydrated with for storage purposes. This field accepts terms listed under microbiological culture medium (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/MICRO_0000067). If the proper descriptor is not listed please use text to describe the sample storage media

Name: sample storage duration
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: sample storage location
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: sample storage solution
NCBI_provided_description: Solution within which sample was stored, if any

Name: sample storage temperature
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: sample subtype
NCBI_provided_description: Name of sample sub-type, e.g., oil phase, water phase, biofilm, not applicable

Name: sample surface moisture
NCBI_provided_description: Degree of water held on a sampled surface, e.g., intermittent moisture, not present, submerged

Name: sampling time outside

Name: sample transport conditions
NCBI_provided_description: Sample transport duration (in days or hrs) and temperature the sample was exposed to (e.g., 5.5 days; 20C)

Name: sample transport container
NCBI_provided_description: Container in which the sample was stored during transport. Indicate the location name, e.g., bottle, cooler, glass vial, plastic vial, vendor supplied container

Name: sample transport duration
NCBI_provided_description: The duration of time from when the sample was collected until processed. Indicate the duration for which the sample was stored written in ISO 8601 format

NCBI_provided_description: Temperature at which sample was transported, e.g., -20 or 4 degree Celsius

Name: sample volume or weight for DNA extraction
NCBI_provided_description: volume (mL) or weight (g) of sample processed for DNA extraction

Name: sampling day weather
NCBI_provided_description: The weather on the sampling day, e.g., clear sky, cloudy, foggy, hail, rain, snow, sleet, sunny, windy

Name: sample well name
NCBI_provided_description: Name of the well where sample was taken, e.g., BXA1123

Name: not_included
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: sample type
NCBI_provided_description: Sample type, such as cell culture, mixed culture, tissue sample, whole organism, single cell, metagenomic assembly

Name: sample use
NCBI_provided_description: dbgap_public dictionary

Name: sanitizer used during postharvest cleaning

NCBI_provided_description: treatment involving an exposure to a particular season (e.g. winter, summer, rabi, rainy etc.)

Name: mean seasonal temperature
NCBI_provided_description: Mean seasonal temperature

Name: sediment type
NCBI_provided_description: information about the sediment type based on major constituents

Name: not_included
NCBI_provided_description: not_included

Name: serogroup

NCBI_provided_description: The type of shading device, e.g., bahama shutters, exterior roll blind, gambrel awning, hood awning, porchroller awning, sarasota shutters, slatted aluminum, solid aluminum awning, sun screen, tree, trellis, venetian awning

NCBI_provided_description: collection design of pooled samples and/or sieve size and amount of sample sieved

Name: silicate

Name: size fraction selected
NCBI_provided_description: Filtering pore size used in sample preparation, e.g., 0-0.22 micrometer

Name: size-fraction lower threshold
NCBI_provided_description: Refers to the mesh/pore size used to pre-filter/pre-sort the sample. Materials larger than the size threshold are excluded from the sample

Name: size-fraction upper threshold
NCBI_provided_description: Refers to the mesh/pore size used to retain the sample. Materials smaller than the size threshold are excluded from the sample

Name: slope aspect
NCBI_provided_description: the direction a slope faces. While looking down a slope use a compass to record the direction you are facing (direction or degrees); e.g., NW or 315°. This measure provides an indication of sun and wind exposure that will influence soil temperature and evapotranspiration.

Name: slope gradient
NCBI_provided_description: commonly called “slope.” The angle between ground surface and a horizontal line (in percent). This is the direction that overland water would flow. This measure is usually taken with a hand level meter or clinometer.

Name: sludge retention time
NCBI_provided_description: the time activated sludge remains in reactor

Name: smoker
NCBI_provided_description: specification of smoking status

Name: sodium

Name: soil conductivity
NCBI_provided_description: Conductivity of soil at time of sampling

Name: soil cover
NCBI_provided_description: Description of the material covering the sampled soil. This field accepts terms under ENVO:00010483, environmental material

Name: soil depth
NCBI_provided_description: The vertical distance below local surface, e.g., for sediment or soil samples depth is measured from sediment or soil surface, respectively. Depth can be reported as an interval for subsurface samples

Name: soil horizon
NCBI_provided_description: specific layer in the land area which measures parallel to the soil surface and possesses physical characteristics which differ from the layers above and beneath
Format: ['', 'O horizon', 'A horizon', 'E horizon', 'B horizon', 'C horizon', 'R layer', 'Permafrost']

Name: soil pH
NCBI_provided_description: The pH of soil at time of sampling

Name: soil sediment porosity
NCBI_provided_description: Porosity of soil or deposited sediment is volume of voids divided by the total volume of sample

Name: soil temperature
NCBI_provided_description: Temperature of soil at the time of sampling

Name: soil texture measurement
NCBI_provided_description: the relative proportion of different grain sizes of mineral particles in a soil, as described using a standard system; express as % sand (50 um to 2 mm), silt (2 um to 50 um), and clay (<2 um) with textural name (e.g., silty clay loam) optional.

Name: soil texture classification
NCBI_provided_description: One of the 12 soil texture classes use to describe soil texture based on the relative proportion of different grain sizes of mineral particles [sand (50 um to 2 mm), silt (2 um to 50 um), and clay (<2 um)] in a soil, e.g., clay, clay loam, loam, loamy sand, sand, sandy clay, sandy clay loam, sandy loam, silt, silty clay, silty clay loam, silt loam

Name: soil texture method
NCBI_provided_description: reference or method used in determining soil texture

Name: soil type
NCBI_provided_description: soil series name or other lower-level classification

Name: soil type method
NCBI_provided_description: reference or method used in determining soil series name or other lower-level classification

Name: solar irradiance
NCBI_provided_description: the amount of solar energy that arrives at a specific area of a surface during a specific time interval

Name: soluble inorganic material
NCBI_provided_description: concentration of substances such as ammonia, road-salt, sea-salt, cyanide, hydrogen sulfide, thiocyanates, thiosulfates, etc.

Name: soluble organic material
NCBI_provided_description: concentration of substances such as urea, fruit sugars, soluble proteins, drugs, pharmaceuticals, etc.

NCBI_provided_description: unique identifier assigned to a material sample used for extracting nucleic acids, and subsequent sequencing. The identifier can refer either to the original material collected or to any derived sub-samples.

Name: source type
NCBI_provided_description: Controlled vocabulary describing the isolation_source. Choose the best fit term: Human, Animal, Food, Environmental, Other, e.g., Food

Format: ['', 'animal as food consumer', 'laboratory animal as food consumer', 'non-food animal as food consumer', 'pet animal as consumer', 'pet fish as consumer', 'pet cat as consumer', 'pet bird as consumer', 'pet dog as consumer', 'sheep or goat as consumer', 'food animal as consumer', 'food fish as consumer', 'poultry as consumer', 'pig as consumer', 'game as consumer', 'rabbit as consumer', 'cattle as consumer', 'horse as consumer', 'human as food consumer', 'adult human as food consumer', 'man as food consumer', 'woman as food consumer', 'senior as food consumer', 'athlete as food consumer', 'bodybuilder as food consumer', 'weight-reducer as food consumer', 'human as food consumer, four years and above', 'teenager as food consumer', 'child as food consumer, less than four years', 'infant or toddler as food consumer', 'toddler as food consumer, 12 months and onwards', 'infant as food consumer', 'missing', 'not applicable', 'not collected', 'not provided', 'restricted access']

NCBI_provided_description: specification of special diet; can include multiple special diets

Name: specifications
NCBI_provided_description: The building specifications, e.g., operation, as built, construction, bid, design, photos

Name: specific humidity
NCBI_provided_description: The mass of water vapour in a unit mass of moist air, usually expressed as grams of vapour per kilogram of air, or, in air conditioning, as grains per pound

Name: specimen voucher
NCBI_provided_description: Identifier for the physical specimen. Use format: "[<institution-code>:[<collection-code>:]]<specimen_id>", eg, "UAM:Mamm:52179". Intended as a reference to the physical specimen that remains after it was analyzed. If the specimen was destroyed in the process of analysis, electronic images (e-vouchers) are an adequate substitute for a physical voucher specimen. Ideally the specimens will be deposited in a curated museum, herbarium, or frozen tissue collection, but often they will remain in a personal or laboratory collection for some time before they are deposited in a curated collection. There are three forms of specimen_voucher qualifiers. If the text of the qualifier includes one or more colons it is a 'structured voucher'. Structured vouchers include institution-codes (and optional collection-codes) taken from a controlled vocabulary maintained by the INSDC that denotes the museum or herbarium collection where the specimen resides, please visit: http://www.insdc.org/controlled-vocabulary-specimenvoucher-qualifier.

Name: antimicrobial phenotype of spike-in bacteria
NCBI_provided_description: Qualitative description of a microbial response to antimicrobial agents. Bacteria may be susceptible or resistant to a broad range of antibiotic drugs or drug classes, with several intermediate states or phases. This field accepts terms under antimicrobial phenotype (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ARO_3004299)

Name: spike-in with antibiotics
NCBI_provided_description: Antimicrobials used in research study to assess effects of exposure on microbiome of a specific site. Please list antimicrobial, common name and/or class and concentration used for spike-in

Name: spike-in organism count
NCBI_provided_description: Total cell count of any organism (or group of organisms) per gram, volume or area of sample, should include name of organism followed by count. The method that was used for the enumeration (e.g., qPCR, atp, mpn, etc.) should also be provided, e.g., total prokaryotes; 3.5e7 cells per ml; qPCR

Name: spike-in growth medium
NCBI_provided_description: A liquid or gel containing nutrients, salts, and other factors formulated to support the growth of microorganisms, cells, or plants (National Cancer Institute Thesaurus). A growth medium is a culture medium which has the disposition to encourage growth of particular bacteria to the exclusion of others in the same growth environment. In this case, list the culture medium used to propagate the spike-in bacteria during preparation of spike-in inoculum. This field accepts terms listed under microbiological culture medium (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/MICRO_0000067). If the proper descriptor is not listed please use text to describe the spike in growth media

Name: spike-in with heavy metals
NCBI_provided_description: Heavy metals used in research study to assess effects of exposure on microbiome of a specific site. Please list heavy metals and concentration used for spike-in

Name: spike in organism
NCBI_provided_description: Taxonomic information about the spike-in organism(s). This field accepts terms under organism (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCIT_C14250). This field also accepts identification numbers from NCBI under https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/taxonomy. Multiple terms can be separated by pipes

Name: spike-in bacterial serovar or serotype
NCBI_provided_description: Taxonomic information about the spike-in organism(s) at the serovar or serotype level. This field accepts terms under organism (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCIT_C14250). This field also accepts identification numbers from NCBI under https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/taxonomy. Multiple terms can be separated by pipes

Name: spike-in microbial strain
NCBI_provided_description: Taxonomic information about the spike-in organism(s) at the strain level. This field accepts terms under organism (http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCIT_C14250). This field also accepts identification numbers from NCBI under https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/taxonomy. Multiple terms can be separated by pipes

Name: source rock depositional environment
NCBI_provided_description: Source rock depositional environment (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Source_rock), e.g., lacustine, fluvioldeltaic, fluviomarine, marine

Name: source rock geological age
NCBI_provided_description: Geological age of source rock (Additional info: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Period_(geology)), e.g., archean, cambrian, carboniferous, cenozoic, cretaceous, devonian, jurassic, mesozoic, neogene, ordovician, paleogene, paleozoic, permian, precambrian, proterozoic, silurian, triassic

Name: source rock kerogen type
NCBI_provided_description: Origin of kerogen. Type I: Algal (aquatic), Type II: planktonic and soft plant material (aquatic or terrestrial), Type III: terrestrial woody/ fibrous plant material (terrestrial), Type IV: oxidized recycled woody debris (terrestrial) (additional information: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kerogen), e.g., type I, type II, type III, type IV

Name: source rock lithology
NCBI_provided_description: Lithology of source rock (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Source_rock), e.g., clastic, carbonate, coal, biosilicieous

Name: standing water regimen

Name: sampling room sterilization method
